## Advanced Improvisation

### Systematic Improvisation Framework

**Material assessment:**
\`\`\`
Available categories:
1. Dedicated medical supplies (use first)
2. Outdoor gear (packs, poles, pads)
3. Clothing (clean, cuttable)
4. Natural materials (sticks, moss, bark)
5. Found items (bottles, containers)

Selection criteria:
- Clean/cleanable
- Appropriate mechanical properties
- Adequate size
- Secure and stay in place
\`\`\`

### Advanced Improvised Techniques

**Improvised traction splint:**
\`\`\`
Indication: Femur fracture (reduces pain, bleeding, muscle spasm)
Materials: Two trekking poles, padding, cordage, ankle hitch
Construction:
1. Pad poles, secure to leg
2. Create ankle hitch (figure-8 or commercial)
3. Apply traction via pole extension or rope system
4. Traction until muscle relaxation, not "normal length"
Monitoring: Pulse, sensation, color checks
\`\`\`

**Improvised pelvic binder:**
\`\`\`
Indication: Unstable pelvic fracture
Materials: Wide strap (pack hip belt, clothing strip)
Position: At level of greater trochanters (not iliac crests)
Tension: Enough to stabilize, not compress
Note: Reduce pelvic volume, tamponade bleeding
\`\`\`

**Improvised nasopharyngeal airway:**
\`\`\`
Materials: Flexible tubing (hydration hose), lubrication
Size: Approximate nostril size, length to tragus
Caution: Not for facial trauma, basilar skull fracture
Note: Commercial NPA vastly preferred
\`\`\`

### Improvisation Limitations

**Know when improvisation inappropriate:**
- When commercial alternative critical (tourniquet)
- When improvised failure high-consequence
- When you lack knowledge/skill for assessment
- When patient can wait for proper equipment

## Quality and Maintenance

### Kit Audit Protocol

**Pre-season:**
\`\`\`
1. Complete inventory against list
2. Check all medication expiration dates
3. Inspect equipment condition
4. Replace used/expired items
5. Update contents based on training
6. Test electronic items (batteries)
\`\`\`

**Post-trip:**
\`\`\`
1. Restock used items
2. Dry wet contents
3. Note any items needed but not carried
4. Document any improvisations used
5. Update kit based on experience
\`\`\`

### Medication Management

**Stability considerations:**
\`\`\`
Heat: Most medications stable to 40C for short periods
Cold: Avoid freezing of liquids
Humidity: Keep medications in sealed containers
Light: Protect light-sensitive items
\`\`\`

**Expiration extension:**
\`\`\`
SLEP studies (military):
- Many medications stable years past expiration
- Solid forms more stable than liquids
- Tetracyclines and liquid antibiotics exception (discard)
- Wilderness context: Some expired medication better than none
Note: Rotate stock, do not rely on expired medications
