Tourniquet selection evidence:
- CAT Gen 7: Most extensively studied
- SOFTT-W: Military alternative, equivalent
- Improvised: 40% failure rate (do not rely on)
\`\`\`

**Hemostatic agent comparison:**
\`\`\`
| Agent | Mechanism | Efficacy | Considerations |
|-------|-----------|----------|----------------|
| Combat Gauze | Kaolin activates XII | 91% | Most studied |
| Celox Gauze | Chitosan adhesion | 88% | Works in coagulopathy |
| Celox A | Chitosan granules | 82% | Older generation |
| QuikClot granules | Zeolite | 75% | Exothermic risk |

Application technique critical:
- Pack wound firmly
- Fill entire wound cavity
- Apply pressure 3+ minutes
- Do not remove, pack over if needed
\`\`\`

### Wound Care Evidence Integration

**Irrigation evidence synthesis:**
\`\`\`
Cochrane systematic review findings:
- Tap water equivalent to sterile saline
- No benefit to antiseptic solutions (may impair healing)
- Higher pressure (5-8 psi) superior to low pressure
- Volume correlated with reduced infection

Practical application:
- Use cleanest available water
- Syringe provides adequate pressure
- Minimum 250ml (ideally 500-1000ml)
- More aggressive irrigation for contaminated wounds
\`\`\`

**Wound closure meta-analysis:**
\`\`\`
Sutures vs staples:
- Cosmetic outcome: Equivalent for non-facial wounds
- Infection rates: Equivalent
- Dehiscence: Equivalent

Tissue adhesive vs sutures (select wounds):
- Cosmetic outcome: Equivalent to superior
- Pain during closure: Less with adhesive
- Limitations: Low-tension, clean wounds only

Timing of closure (recent evidence):
- Traditional "6-8 hour golden period" oversimplified
- Clean wounds: Safe closure to 18-24 hours
- Highly contaminated: Delayed primary closure preferred
- Wilderness consideration: Adequate cleaning more important than timing
\`\`\`

### Pharmacology for Kit Selection

**NSAID pharmacokinetics:**
\`\`\`
| Parameter | Ibuprofen | Naproxen | Ketorolac |
|-----------|-----------|----------|-----------|
| Onset | 30-60 min | 60 min | 30-60 min |
| Peak | 1-2 hr | 2-4 hr | 1-2 hr |
| Duration | 4-6 hr | 8-12 hr | 4-6 hr |
| Half-life | 2 hr | 12-17 hr | 5 hr |

Selection rationale:
- Ibuprofen: Best balance of efficacy, onset, and safety
- Naproxen: Longer duration, less frequent dosing
- Ketorolac (Rx): Superior for acute pain, short-term only
\`\`\`

**Altitude medication evidence:**
\`\`\`
Acetazolamide mechanism and evidence:
- Carbonic anhydrase inhibition
- Renal bicarbonate wasting -> metabolic acidosis
- Compensatory hyperventilation
- Effectively accelerates acclimatization

Dose-response (meta-analysis):
- 125mg BID: RR 0.52 for AMS
- 250mg BID: RR 0.45 for AMS
- 375mg BID: No additional benefit, more side effects
Conclusion: 125-250mg BID optimal

PDE-5 inhibitors for HAPE:
- Sildenafil: Effective for HAPE prophylaxis and treatment
- Tadalafil: Longer duration, once-daily dosing
- Mechanism: Pulmonary vasodilation via NO pathway
\`\`\`

### Antibiotic Selection for Wilderness Kits

**Evidence-based empiric selections:**
\`\`\`
Wound infection:
- First choice: Amoxicillin-clavulanate 875/125 BID
- Alternative: Cephalexin 500mg QID (if penicillin tolerant)
- Cover: Staph, Strep, some anaerobes

Traveler's diarrhea:
- Azithromycin 500mg daily x 3 (broader coverage)
- Ciprofloxacin 500mg BID x 3 (if fluoroquinolone appropriate)
- Rifaximin 200mg TID x 3 (non-invasive)

UTI:
- Nitrofurantoin 100mg BID x 5 (resistance low)
- Trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole DS BID x 3 (if susceptible)
- Ciprofloxacin 250mg BID x 3 (broader coverage)

Note: Antibiotic selection requires medical provider assessment
\`\`\`

## Advanced Kit Optimization

### Decision Analysis Framework

**Expected value calculation:**
\`\`\`
EV = Sigma(Pi * Vi) - Cost(weight, bulk, $)

Where:
Pi = Probability of scenario i
Vi = Value of item in scenario i (lives saved, suffering reduced)
Cost = Burden of carrying item

Example - Tourniquet:
P(need) = 0.001 per person-day
V(if needed) = Life saved, or death prevented = Very high
Cost = 78g, $30
EV = Strongly positive (despite low probability)
\`\`\`

### Population-Based Kit Design

**Epidemiology-driven quantities:**
\`\`\`
Based on wilderness injury data:
- Soft tissue injuries: 40% of encounters
- Musculoskeletal: 25%
- Environmental: 15%
- GI: 10%
- Other: 10%

Kit design implication:
- High inventory: Wound care supplies (bandages, tape)
- Moderate inventory: Splinting, elastic bandages
- Lower inventory: Specialized items (used less often)
- Always carry: Life-saving items regardless of probability
\`\`\`

### Systematic Improvisation Methodology

**Decision tree for improvisation:**
\`\`\`
Is dedicated item available?
  YES -> Use dedicated item
  NO -> Understand function needed
        |
        v
        Identify candidate materials
        |
        v
        Assess material properties
        - Mechanical (strength, flexibility)
        - Cleanliness (sterile vs. clean vs. contaminated)
        - Durability (will it last?)
        |
        v
        Modify technique for material
        |
        v
        Monitor closely for failure
\`\`\`

**Improvisation evidence:**
\`\`\`
Few studies directly compare improvised vs. commercial
Available data:
- Improvised tourniquets: 40% failure rate
- Improvised splints: Generally adequate when properly constructed
- Improvised wound closure: Case series suggest reasonable outcomes

Conclusion:
- Carry commercial items for critical functions (tourniquet)
- Improvisation acceptable for less critical items
- Skill and creativity extend kit capability
\`\`\`

### Quality Metrics for Kit Evaluation

**Outcome-based assessment:**
\`\`\`
Ideal metrics:
- Patient outcomes (hard to measure)
- Completion of care episodes
- Unanticipated item needs
- Weight efficiency (outcomes/kg)

Process metrics:
- Time to access needed items
- Item availability when needed
- Expiration/degradation rates
- User confidence and competence
\`\`\`

## Advanced Considerations

### Austere Environment Modifications

**Extended duration (weeks):**
\`\`\`
Medication quantities: Full course for likely conditions
Resupply planning: Cache points, evacuation options
Expiration management: Rotate stock, extend as needed
Weight distribution: Shared group carry
\`\`\`

**Extreme cold:**
\`\`\`
Medication protection: Body warmth storage
Liquid medications: Avoid or insulate
Packaging: Cold can make plastic brittle
Batteries: Cold reduces capacity
\`\`\`

**Tropical/marine:**
\`\`\`
Humidity: Sealed containers essential
Heat: Medication stability considerations
Specific risks: Marine envenomation, tropical infections
Waterproofing: All items protected
\`\`\`

### Legal and Ethical Considerations

**Scope of practice:**
\`\`\`
Kit contents should match:
- Provider training and certification
- Legal authority in jurisdiction
- Good Samaritan coverage understanding

Prescription medications:
- Carry only with valid prescription
- Document medical direction if available
- Understand liability exposure
\`\`\`

**Documentation importance:**
\`\`\`
Medical records in wilderness:
- Document assessments and treatments
- Track vital signs and trends
- Note medication administration
- Record patient response
- Essential for continuity of care
